  </code></synopsis>
  <p>Calculates the cross product between the two vectors <code>u</code> and <code>v</code>.</p>  <p>The cross product is a vector perpendicular to both <code>u</code> and <code>v</code>. This
can be useful for calculating the normal of a polygon by creating
two vectors in its plane using the polygons vertices and taking
their cross product.</p>  <p>If the two vectors are parallel then the cross product is 0.</p>  <p>You can use a right hand rule to determine which direction the
perpendicular vector will point: If you place the two vectors tail,
to tail and imagine grabbing the perpendicular line that extends
through the common tail with your right hand such that you fingers
rotate in the direction from <code>u</code> to <code>v</code> then the resulting vector
points along your extended thumb.</p>
  <p>Since 1.4</p>
